com.analog.lyric.collect

Class ConstructorRegistry<T>

  • java.lang.Object
    • java.util.AbstractMap<java.lang.String,java.lang.reflect.Constructor<T>>
      • com.analog.lyric.collect.ConstructorRegistry<T>
  • Type Parameters:
    T - is the super class of all of the classes in the registry.
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.util.Map<java.lang.String,java.lang.reflect.Constructor<T>>
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    DimpleSolverRegistry, FactorFunctionRegistry

    @ThreadSafe
public class ConstructorRegistry<T>
extends java.util.AbstractMap<java.lang.String,java.lang.reflect.Constructor<T>>
    Simple registry mapping class names to constructor instances.

    Note that Map methods such as containsKey(java.lang.Object), containsValue(java.lang.Object), keySet(), values(), entrySet(), and size() will only reflect keys that have been explicitly looked up using one of get(java.lang.Object), getClass(java.lang.String), instantiate(java.lang.String) or loadAll().

    Since:
    0.07

      • get

        @NonNullByDefault(value=false)
@Nullable
public final java.lang.reflect.Constructor<T> get(java.lang.Object className)
        Looks up no-argument constructor for named class.

        If className is a fully qualified name referring to a class with an accessible constructor that takes no arguments, that constructor will be returned. Otherwise, this will searches all of the registry's packages (see getPackages()) for class with given className and compatible constructor. Returns first match or null if none is found.

        Specified by:
        get in interface java.util.Map<java.lang.String,java.lang.reflect.Constructor<T>>
        Overrides:
        get in class java.util.AbstractMap<java.lang.String,java.lang.reflect.Constructor<T>>
        Parameters:
        className - is either the unqualified or fully qualified name of the class whose constructor is sought.
        See Also:
        get(String, Class[])

      • get

        @Nullable
public final java.lang.reflect.Constructor<T> get(java.lang.String className,
                                            java.lang.Class<?>[] formalParameters)
        Looks up constructor for named class with specified formal parameters.

        If className is a fully qualified name referring to a class with an accessible constructor that takes no arguments, that constructor will be returned. Otherwise, this will searches all of the registry's packages (see getPackages()) for class with given className and compatible constructor. Returns first match or null if none is found.

        Parameters:
        className - is either the unqualified or fully qualified name of the class whose constructor is sought.
        formalParameters - are the declared types of the parameters to the constructor. Note that these must match exactly.
        See Also:
        get(String, Class[])

        Parameters:
